			1.2.1.5 buqs 3 Gravebone Decks "Shifting with the Meta"
Ok so I love Gravebone and don't really like to play other heroes. Now that we have 3 deck slots per hero I decided to put together 3 decks thy I can use to combat the meta, since I don't play other heroes. Hope you enjoy them. 

				1.2.1.5.1 Deck Slot 1: Sanctuary Build

Gravebone x1

Allies: (18)
Ironhide Karash x4
Gargoyle x4
Sun-Blighted One x4
Death Mage Thaddeus x3
Shadow Knight x2

Abilities/Items/Attachments: (22)
Fireball x4
Lightning Strike x4
Supernova x3
Consuming Fear x2
Sanctuary x4
Tome of Knowledge x4
Sacrificial Lamb x2

Sleeve: Blood Moon

TOTAL: 41

ALT: -2 SK, +2 PB

Resource Curve:
1cc - 0
2cc - 16
3cc - 15
4cc - 4
5cc - 5

General Play Style:

The general idea is that you are going to spam you SBO's to create a ping cycle. This normally doesn't work too well because your also giving your opponent SE. The counter to this is Sanctuary. This card is my favorite at the moment. You can chain these together negating opponents hero ability use (which is useful against all heroes, except Jerry). The beauty is that you can use your ability in between, so basically you bring the ping SBO monster back from the graveyard but opponent can't counter with SE assistance. SK is extra meat but also to bring back the ping twin or gargoyle depending on matchup. Deck uses a lot of 3cc allis and relies heavily on drawing on Tok to dig for the sanctuaries so you can chain them, this (and SBO) is reason for limited 5cc allies in deck. SK in opening hand is usually a sac card.

A part of Gravebones biggest strength is his ability to revive a fatty into play, this is also a big weakness as most seasoned players have learned ways to deal with the predictable play patterns of Gravebone. Lots of heroes rely on their hero ability to help put the fatty back into the ground and generally it works. During matches you will not be able to stop your opposing hero from using their ability, but what you are trying to do is prevent it's use at a critical time to help turn the tide in your favor. Timing is more difficult with opponents with cost of 3SE so they shoot off 1-2 uses before you can start stalling them, and sometimes depending on hand/board/situation it's better to force opponent to use ability early and set them up for the next cycle. 

Lightning strike is most important ability on any matchup you think an opponent is using FT. 

Alt version using Plasma Behemoths in lieu of SK. Gives more meat to the build, however turns away from the drawing force needed to fuel the engine to dig for sanctuaries.

Some of the Medium to Good Matchups:

Amber. An Amber without a buffed JD is pretty weak. What's really nice is even though ambers ability only cost 3se she can't /doesn't typically use her ability until turn 4 with JD. If you are able to setup sanctuary early you can put a really big dent into her game plan and you'll notice she plays her turns more slowly, having to create an alternative game plan for the matchup. Even if you don't get sanctuaries you should still be able to play SBOs freely (though they die to buffed weapons) because extra SE really is no use to Amber as she has to go through her weapons to buff another one, so this SBO benefits you more in this one. 

Gwen (solo). A Gwen without a buffed weapon is pretty weak and rapid fire just turns her into CotC Baduru. Now that being said her saving grace is ITF. She can use these to stall out sanctuaries, and if she is using night prowler she can flip the switch on you. This matchup is still favored towards you. SBO ping and nova bypass ITF (finishing moves). Sac lamb is a good card to prevent any healing from soul seeker and dig more sanctuaries.

Eladwen. Sanctuary turns Eladwen into Gravebone....what this means is since she cannot use her ability to help control the board, she has to start directing her burn toward your allies. The more burn she uses this way the higher probability you will win. If you go second, you will want to play Ironhide, gargoyle, tok + sanctuary, draw + SBO, draw +, etc..... The early hard to kills will set you up nicely, and on 4 block her ice stall advantage. Even if she wipes on 5 you claim the board because it will be empty on your turn.

Lance. Without his hasted raven, he's just not as strong. Stop thief! Can't destroy Sanctuary, Ironhide beats down anklebreakers, CF for raven or aeons. I haven't run into any Spelleater bands but board seems to be easier to regain/control so I'm sure it will be as much a problem.

Logan. Logan lost a lot of his strength when his ability was changed to 4SE. While DP has brought him some new toys his ability remains his strength and the board is dependent on his having access to this + weapons. Combined with Killing Spree essentially he could have great control, but by shutting this down with Sanctuary he will have a hard time regaining board after his early setup.

Baduruu. Sanctuary works really well against Baduruu. Normally his ability is used as a tempo boost he needs to help control the early and late game. By using sanctuary we are removing not only the tempo but also the weapon boost maximizing the effectiveness of IK and Gargoyles to beat down the weapon durability of the unbuffed weapons. Res D isn't really a problem for this deck because all the allies are super cheap, as well as drawing, sanctuary and CF. Snare trap is a motha, so you kinda have to be caution on what you play when you think it's out. Ironhide/DMT are usually my trap disarmer if possible. I've yet to be afraid to play SBO for fear of giving Baduruu more SE. LS are still going to be key spells because of FT, but nova will be equally important for disrupting board as well as denying potential healing from SS. 

Gravebone. If your opponents name is buqs.....just rage quit early and deny him any winnings. On a serious note, taking away GBs hero ability can ruin him for the whole game. He is typically a hero that doesn't use his ability until turn 5-7 for the first time, so a lot of times you can wait to lock his ability out with Sanctuary. Additionally without any access to healing the ping will really start to wear down on him. While playing, remember to keep some combo damage options available. Opponent will more than likely be playing with some fatties/hard to kill allies and most of ours dont deal much damage on their own.

Darkclaw. Sanctuary totally wrecks a the strength of a solo Darkclaw build. Without the weapon buff and ambush Darkclaw will really take a beating. Combine this with tech items like severed ties for lone wolf and this should be a fairly favorable matchup.

Moonstalker. As a Mage this is already a favorable matchup, if your using the PB build then it is even more favorable. SBO is a bit counter productive because it increases the hiding potential of moon, but if you have board and are able to lock out the stall with sanctuaries you can just drop the hammer hard. If it's an allied moon, then matchup becomes unfavorable.

Zaladar. This one can be difficult depending on skill level of your opponent. This is not necessarily the perfect build against Zaladar but it stands a very good chance against him. Zaladar relies on his ability more than most heroes and actually runs a full set of shadow font and possibly other things that help him accumulate SE. Sanctuary is a very effective card against Zaladar because it really minimizes the effectiveness of those cards. SBO is actually not a good ally to revive in this matchup because he comes back with the 5 attack which is just begging for a mind control. I would only revive him if I'm planning on using a sac lamb on him for ping + draw. Usually I use SBOs to accelerate gargoyle revivals, but I try to stagger them in play, so they take reduced damage at different rates, hence dying at different turns and revival at different turns. This is guaranteed to have FT in this matchup, so save them LS.....you will need them.
Last edited by Buqs; 10-12-2013 at 02:41 AM.

				1.2.1.5.2 Deck Slot 2: Portal Build

Gravebone x1

Allies: (18)
Ironhide Karash x4
Bad Wolf x3
Death Collector x3
Rust Weevil x1
Shadow Knight x3
Molten Destroyer x2
Kairos x1
Colossus x1

Abilities/Items/Attachments: (22)
Portal x4
Fireball x4
Lightning Strike x3
Supernova x2
Shriek x1
Sacrificial Lamb x2
Tome of Knowledge x2
Bad Santa x1
Consuming Fear x3

Sleeve: Blood Moon

TOTAL: 41

Casting Cost:
1cc - 1
2cc - 12
3cc - 11
4cc - 7
5cc - 7
6cc - 2

General Play Style:

A portal build is by far my favorite way to play the game so it will always have a home for one of my Gravebone deck slots. Since DPs release it has been the least played of my 3 decks so it it not as developed as the other 2 decks are and still likely to evolve. 

The early game for Gravebone never really changes. We always want to try and get some allies down early or at least use our DD and/or CF to minimize the damage of opponents early game. Gravebone really needs to save as much HP as possible to help him transition to the mid-late game where he can become more dangerous, so if you have to use ability early (turn 4/5) its worth it. Doesnt really matter saving for turn 6-7 if your dead. Unlike the other 2 build this one use more aggressive allies (cc = to attack power) to maximize effectiveness through portal. SK is also included because he helps to draw (pseudo) allies needed to fuel portals duration. alot of times you want to retrieve either low cost allies or SKs, while saving Gbs ability for MDs, Kairos or what ever other ally is needed at the moment. This Gravebone has the ability to recreate a broken SK loop more easily than any other GB or other hero build because of the combination of Hero ability, SK and DC. {Examples, GB ability [on SK] + Sac Lamb + SK; GB ability and/or Death Collector ability on top allies to get to a buried SK, then play SK from hand.} The portal build is also a fragile build (allies are typically easy to kill) so we include some more durable allies in the form of MD and Kairos. Both provide a different form of retaliation which can be useful to survive the day. Ive reduced ToKs from 3 to 2 swapping 1 for BS. Sometimes you really just need that quick draw to help reload to maximize portals effectiveness and Tok can be to slow. 

I personally dont like to play with Item D other than shriek (which usually I use 2 except for sanctuary build which uses none). So what Ive done for this build is mixed things up a bit. Portal + allies make sense on multiple levels, so Ive brought in RW and Colossus for their respective abilities. All are different in what they do, but also more importantly in their cost (SoV 1, RW 3 and SC 6). RW is the new comer to my recent change in the deck (replacing 1BW, 1SoV and adding 1CF) TBD if hes staying.

CF is a great card to play with portal. It is cheap enough control card to play with other allies and also (more often than not) affords the oppotunity for your allies to go for the hero and ignore opponents allies. I was looking for a way to up the count to 3 (see changes in above paragraph).

The introduction of FT kinda requires that all mages use LS. In lieu of 4 though I only use 3 because with portal I have the opportunity to use allies to deal with FTs. Nova + GB is still a good move, and even better when you use portal send all allies for throat (opponents spend time removing your threats) and then when portal duration ends, nova (more damage) + revive (board).

Some of the Medium to Good Matchups:

Boris (allied). Boris is generally played with a fast paced tempo build geared towards mid late game swarm / dominance. He generally has a few spots in his game plan where you can swing the game in your favor. Most notably these are the turns when he plays blood frenzy (usually turn 3/4), or when he has a weak board and only plays kings pride or enrage. He also has great tempo disrupters like cb and retreat, as well as his hero ability and dragons tooth. To combat this control machine we attempt to match his tempo both in board as well as draw. We use a portal build as we can generally get the most use of our allies before Boris can begin controlling them. We also use a lot of aggressive allies to maximize damage output from portal. Drawing will come from SKs as well as sac lambs (CBed allies). LS not favorable because it does not kill most of the allies Boris uses on its own so we lean more on portal/nova instead. 

Victor. Victor will be a fairly even matchup but should be favored towards Gravebone. IK and Md are going to be a pain for Victor to deal with so he will end up having to use poison arrows on IK and TPS/hero ability on Mds which will still provide a double ping. Additionally you got a potential SK loop which can cause Victor to run out of control answers and eventually loose the game. A portal build to reduce the effectiveness of the control aspect that Victor relies on to manipulate the game. Shriek is included to remove snare trap at key points in the game, but also useful if Victor is running WOTF. Sac Lamb and Nova are here for mainly for removing healing options from Victor but Nova can produce great control allowing some shots on hero before wiping and reviving your own ally (preferably a MD).

Nishaven. The fact that Nish has a slow charge ability really dicates how you can play this game. Nishs ability will kill all your early board allies fairly easily (low health). Typically I will play a board just before Nish has a full charge as a deterent for him to use his ability as a hasted ally (+ ally revive) can potentially negate his ability wipe + ally play, plus you have yet another turn of duration for portal. Now Nish is not a frequently played hero so the builds are not consitant yet. If it is a portal build, usually whoever plays the portal second (and can capture the board) will win the game. If Nish is playing a Vow build, your changes are greatly reduced and the matchup becomes medium to worse. VoW negates portal slows traditional play, probably has retreats and is probably playing with DoT abilities. Win-able but a long hard game.

Jericho. The long game isn't there for Jericho like his counterpart Zhanna. Your aggressive allies should be able to either cotrol the board or absorb some damage while you are building your resources for a board wipe. Jerry's late game allies are typically gong to come out one at a time and you should be able to control or possibly even ignore them and just go straight for hero. CF is not a good choice in this matchup. Jerry can remove with his ability, but he also has option of ALR. This one you may lose simply because there are not enough Jerry players out and about and people dont know what to do when they see him.

Zhanna. You want to take advantage of Zhanna early and deal as much damage as possible. Gravebone has the opportunity to flood the board after tidal wave which is increased by cards like portal. A late game KP can sometimes mean trouble but a carefully timed Colossus can keep her board pace slowed. SK looping will be the typical form of drawing, and potential damaging source if you've got a portal in play. Also try to save fireballs and LS for end game mass damage that KP can't prevent. Save your single BS and try to save the Sac Lamb, you may need them. 

Logan. Logan is going to want to try and control the board. Portal allows us to deal the damage prior to allies being controlled. Logan has the potential to own the board so, nova plays a big part in this game plan. This is typically a matchup where you'll want to portal rush and follow up with nova. The only time this could become problematic is if it is a rampage build. Your cheap allies are like pac-man pellets. Combat this by switching to burn mode and only reviving MDs (Kairos depending on opponents SE) and or getting resources high enough to deal some big unhealable damage through portal.

Banebow. This will not be easy by any stretch of the imagination, but portal affords the best opportunity for Gravebone to deal with Banebow. BB will still be able to heal from your allies, but control aspect of BBs game will come after your allies have been summoned. Snare trap will be problematic for your little guys, FT + BB ability + Bow will be problematic for your big guys (also TPS). He even has shrieks for your portals. This doesnt sound like a good matchup, but I find this is the best shot youve (or at least me) got. Hit hard and fast. If you let him get setup and start drawing alot (WOTF), hell just get all the tools needed to beat you easier.

Gravebone. While most GB builds will typically take the traditional Fatty build this portal build is a hybrid of sorts to that concept. Portal affords the opportunity to aggressively take the board in ways that nova does not. Allies though portal to take out his allies but you put a body on the board and you did not take 5 damage. We still have nova in the deck because a fatty build is still a challenge but the goal is to be able to be the last one to use hero ability. Typically this means opponent has run out of options and you will quickly end the match once the board remains yours.

Darkclaw. Like Boris, DC generally is able to use a lot of control features to allies on the board. Portal lets us allow our allies to attack first and minimizes DCs effectiveness. Lots of big allies so you should be able to punch with some force. MD is great if EA is on the board for some DoT effects reducing effectiveness of Lone Wolf. Recycle them with GB ability and SKs. Try to save abilities for massive DD damage all at once or after portal expiration. Nova/Sac Lamb good for freeing up allies disabled with CP. IK and Kairos are great during turns DC does not have buffed teeth. Colossus can absorb damage or wreak some havock on Dcs gameplan.

				1.2.1.5.3 Deck Slot 3: Fatty Build

Gravebone x1

Allies: (17)
Ironhide x4
Gargoyle x4
Morbid Acolyte x3
Plasma Behemoth x4
Kairos x1
Ogloth x1

Abilities/Items/Attachments: (23)
Fireball x4
Lightning Strike x4
Nova x3
Tome of Knowledge x3
Sac Lamb x2
Consuming Fear x3
Bloodthirsty x2
Shriek x2

Sleeve: Blood Moon

TOTAL: 41

Resource Curve:
1cc - 2
2cc - 12
3cc - 13
4cc - 4
5cc - 7
6cc - 2

General Play Style:

This deck is a traditional fatty build. It has good early game with allies, abilities and CF. PB is the star of this deck. He has potential to deal with multiple targets and deal massive damage, and with the inclusion of bloodthirsty he can quickly get out of control and help you draw some cards at the same time. Oggy plays a similar role to PB. The higher health means you can still oggy bomb and bloodthirsty with ability can quickly get his attack/health levels up. Kairos is also in because I prefer not to play with ST or get caught with 2 unique high cost allies. While BT can be good with Kairos it's not really as great with other 2 allies. Kairos is good because of high health, steadfast and retaliation damage. GBs ability lends the opportunity to stall with bloodthirsty in hand and wait until you get the board to play it safely. Nova + ability pretty much guarantees this can happen often. 

Some of the Medium to Good Matchups:

Amber. We've got a large number of hard to kill allies so they will generally require 2 sources of damage to kill. CB can minimize the effectiveness of PB but they must be completely killed to be non-threatening, which means you can revive them often. Amber will typically use allies lite on HP so nova can easily reset the board, also bloodthirsty can assist in keeping pace on draw. Kairos can reduce the chances of Amber death racing if you can get to him and he doesn't get CBed.

Gwen. This match really all depends on if Gwen is playing with ITF and/or how much damage you can put down before she gets set up. Typically shes got until turn 6 before she takes off and GB has enough early game to put the pressure on. Bazaar should be shrieked immediately. Save your Sac Lamb/Novas for denying Gwen healing opportunities. Nova is also able to deal damage and bypass ITF. Kairos is great for retaliation attacking Gwen. He will take a beating too, but he helps to reduce the weapon durability much faster.

Nishaven. We are going to combat Nish with lots of hard to kill allies. most allies are going to require 5+ damage to remove which put them just out of nish blast range. Nish typically has a rush deck, or a high costing deck. The high cost version may be solo with either Vow or DoU, Vow version can become difficult if he gets set up properly. Rush version is easier as Nish can't control your allies like Eladwen can, and he also has to have a higher resource count. Drawing on ToK becomes too slow of a draw for this, so he may be playing with bad santas.

Lance. Morbid Acolyte and PB are the stars in this matchup. They are able to bypass the stealth effects of Lances ability and both generally are allies Lance want completely removed from the board. IK is another ally the performs well against lance because he is immune to anklebreakers. He also generally becomes the target of an assassination or hasted ally attack depending on the state of the game. Shriek is for IGG and CF can really assist in numbing the effects of ravens (as can MA). This is a much more winable matchup than a CotC Lance.

Serena. This can be a good matchup for you. Weve got 6 good fatties but really PB is best followed by Kairos. PB again will be the superstar. A buffed weapon is not strong enough to take out PB on its own so Serena will be forced to disable with anklebreakers or combo up to take him out until he is removed from board. Kairos is decent, as Serena may decide to go for the hero, force discard, then deal with combat to Kairos as a 4/4 HP swap. Black Garb can be problematic, so you will may want to use a shriek on this at a key point in the game. But do remember she is probably holding onto another one so make sure the damage is large enough to justify its use (since you would not be using on IGG). If you can get ahead on the board with a few allies you can really make Serena suffer but she does have the tools to potentially own you. Skill of Serena player is heavily a determining factor in this one.

Ter Adun. PB is king in this matchup. Your not going to have a reliable draw engine so slow playing will kinda be forced on you. PBs ability is unaffected by attack modifiers (CB, Punishers Gauntlets, etc) so you will typically have a consistant source of damage and the 5 health usually mean 1-2 turns of surviveability.

Gravebone. OK so this deck has the tools to deal with a Gravebone. Some key allies will be Oggy and Kairos because of their nova surviveability. PB is still good too. This matchup will typically go to howmever can get setup properly first.

Darkclaw. A solo darkclaw should not present a ton of problems. If you can get your allies down early and put the beating on him. IK and Gargs are not affected by an unbuffed WBT so swing away. They will become the targets for NYRM. Captured prey can be troublesome because it shuts down PB completely (as well as DCs hero buff w/ speedstrike), but we've got enough of them to get a rotation going to get the big damage in. You've also got shriek which you can use a critical points for WBT or EA, basically when certain allies are about to die.

Moonstalker. As a Mage this is already a favorable matchup and cycling PB just isn't even fair.
MA is primary board choice over Gargoyle for any allies that may be included in opponents deck (I usually try to keep 1 MA on board at all times. Once PB is in graveyard he becomes primary revive and MAs should be played from hand as support. Shriek for stall tactics if board is set up for big damage, or for EA to reduce DoTs on your allies. 

Elementalis. This is probably the best shot GB has at good matchups vs Elementalis, which is only better if opponent has a bad opening. The really hard to kill allies that Elementalis produces usually means you are fighting from behind and having to use DD to help chop down the HP of those allies so that you can kill them off with some form of combo technique. If you can drop PB on empty board and have him stick for a turn or 2 while you build momentum you can get the win. CF becomes a big assistance in this matchup, but be careful about leaving opposing allies alive because of Superfocus. If Elementalis build is Sanctuary/Interference build you are probably in for some trouble.

Zaladar. This matchup has tons of things that Zal hates. Lots of hard to kills Gargoyles and MA, and PB has low attack so retaliation from MC is low. Zal still has a shot at winning but he's going to sweat and it should be a close match.

---------

Majiya is probably the worst matchup for these 3 decks.

