		1.2.2 Majiya 

			1.2.2.1 ✫MAJIYA✫ easy 300 rating. 
4 Firesnake
4 Gargoyle
3 Death Mage
3 Plasma Behemot
4 Fireball
4 Lightning Strike
3 Super Nova
4 Tome of Knowledge
3 Ley Line Nexus
2 Shriek
2 Sever Ties
3 Dagger of Unmaking

❆ Firesnake: very good T1 when going second, kill Kris, give space in your hand if your opponent want to Santa Bomb, think twice before summoning it vs Shadow, Carniboars enjoy eating them. Also useful in late game, if you draw it and have far enought ressources to summon it, it gave lots of advantage like destroying armor, weapons, distracting opponent from targeting your hero sometimes, ans give the +1 attack which can give you the victory in close game.

❆ Gargoyle: best T3 drop so far, try to not summon two of them if you see Banebow letting his shadow energy growing to 5

❆ Death Mage: one of my favourite ally, summoning him T3 is a bad idea, but if you have nothing better to do...synergize well with Majiya's ability, also good to kill a T3 Priest of the Light when you have a gargoyle on the board. Nice meat shield too since he can do his 1 damage when summoning

❆ Plasma Behemot: wins game, haha, one PB on the board trigger Tidal Wave , against wulven if they don't have Captured Prey in hand it's near gg for you, only way to deal with it for warriors is Retreat, cause crippling blow is just a joke on PB, auto sac vs Elementals, or at least summon if you have already a Dagger of Unmaking out, against Mage try to keep one to summon it right after a Super Nova, but it's better to sac it in most games, better make your ressources grow to burn the opponent before he burns you down.

❆ Fireball: never cast it T3 on the hero, it's dumb, or use an other deck focused on rush. It's better to skip the turn than wasting a Fireball which can help you the next turn to keep the board in control. T4 Fireball + attack with gargoyle to kill an opponent's Gargoyle is good.

❆ Lightning Strike: well.. 6 damages for 4cc.. What to say more? Obvious move, Majiya's ability + LS to kill a Gargoyle

❆ Super Nova: auto sac one in early game if going first, you'll have what you need to keep board in check without using it before T6~7, good game finisher, save ass by making draw when you're going to lose. Majiya's ability + Super Nova kill everything (except Sandworms, but with only one hp left, he's a good as dead)

❆ Tome of Knowledge: usually cast T2, if your opponent Shriek it he will lose one ressources, that good enought to let him destroying it, , Human Wariors, Mage and Hunter can't destroy it, only Rogue and Priest can, so wait T4 to cast + use ability or even later.

❆ Ley Line Nexus: never sac against Hunter and Rogue, against others heroes i always sac my first to keep allies and spells in hand.

❆ Shriek: only 2 of them, cause i don't like losing ressources early, and never shriek a Tome of Knowledge, WotF or other stuff except Witzen Staff or a Portal or Ill Goten Gain. If opponent cast Bazaar, smile and enjoy the free burn. After reaching 5~6 ressources shriek what you feel like disturbing.

❆ Sever Ties: auto sac vs Mage, Rogue, Priest, a must keep vs Wulven (Lone Wolf, Captured Prey -> try to wait 7 ressources to use it on a PB so you can use his ability, no need to hury most of the time), Gwen and Warriors, if you're lucky you destroy a Blood Frenzy as soon as they cast it, if not, then do as you feel like, Blood Frenzy, if you have board control wait for an Enrage, vs Amber you can also use it on an ally to destroy a weapon without using destruction item. Vs Elemental, it's good to keep on in hand if you have something better to sac (like a Firesnake, Shriek or Tome of Knowledge (<-only if you don't have problem to see your ToK shrieked next turn)), i saw some deck using Life Infusion on Gargoyle, lol)

❆ Dagger of Unmaking: try to keep one in hand if draw early. If your opponent doesn't cat allies, use it on the hero, just keep 1 durability


Strategy: go for board control in early game and deal few damages to the hero, from midle game to late game go for the throat. This deck is near unbeatable if your opponent want to burn you quickly.

			1.2.2.2 Portal Majiya

				1.2.2.2.1 Raphael Majere's "Brutal Portal" Deck (WC Top 8)

http://www.shadowera.com/showthread.php?16062-Raphael-Majere-s-quot-Brutal-Portal-quot-Deck-(WC-Top-8)
Firstly, major props to iClipse who beat me in Rd 3 of WC finals! His Zhanna is top-notched. He is official the "Slayer of RaphM". I think we've met in a few official Bo3 and I've never beaten him. 

Someone better do a video series on Game 1 and Game 2 that I (Raphael Majere3) played with iClipse! Game 1 shows perfectly how Zhanna should be played vs Mages. Game 2 shows how the mage can adjust and win vs Zhanna. Many key lessons there. Better watch those games now; before iClipse and I play so many games that those games gets wiped off the records. 

(Notes: this deck is designed for WC, not for QM. For beginners, or players interested to play Portal Maj in QM, I will post my deck at the bottom of this post.)

Major THANKS to my Portal Maj teacher, Oblio91, my guild brother, he basically gave the deck to me and taught me a lot that I didn't know; despite being 'supposedly' an expert at Maj.

Ok, onto my deck, 

Majiya x1

Gargoyle x 4
Death Mage x 4
Shadow Knight x 4
Brutal Minotaur x 2
Fireball x 4
Lightning Strike x 4
tome x 3
Portal x 4
Shriek of Vengeance x 3
Acid Jet x 2
Lamb x 3
nova x 2

40 cards 

Shocking facts:

No brut.
No LLN.
Only 3 Tome?!


Explanations (for the intermediate/advanced player)

a. No bruts. They cannot injure gargs and if I cast them late in the game, they might mess up the graveyard order. The key win con combo in this deck is the SK recycler combo (Credits to Blanketeffect for this), and I do NOT want to recycle a silly brut. I want SK to bring back SK or a BM.

b. Why jet over LLN? It cost less, I dont need the draw and more importantly, jet takes out JD, woft, and wiz staff. Enough said.

c. To play my deck well, you need to learn how to play deathrace Maj first. I was placed second in first ever 1.5 Test Server tourney with the "Deathracer Maj". The deck list is here: http://www.shadowera.com/showthread....l=1#post164151

Deck list:

The Gang of 4 x 4: Brut, Garg, Bad Wulf, DMT.
The Burn: FB. LS, Nova "the 12 Burn"
The Draw x 4: Sac Lamb, Research (Research is not good, change it to BS, see below)
Tech: 3 LLN. (specficially for Spelleater bands)



PS: I re-made this deck; removed the Tome and added 4 BS to make the deck even faster. I played it in Swiss Rds of WC. This deck is still good. Very fast. Very fun to play too..

Long story made shorter: you need to learn how to play deathrace maj cos in this Brutal Portal deck, you can switch to deathrace mode. Like how I did in game 2 vs iClipse and managed to win that.

d. Why 3 Tome and 3 Sac lamb?

As oblio told me, sometimes the tome gets destroyed even before it gets used. Plus, when 1 tome is in play, drawing another one is useless. Sac lamb is crucial for deathracing. attack with ally, then sac it. or sac lamb a crippled/frozen/nulled ally. Draw 3.

e. Key combo of this deck

The infinite Recycle combo of SKs. Watch the games of winners of WC Wildcards 1 and 2. Greymouser and AA1 Larus. They play it beautifully. It does not matter if your opponent has a SS bow or Anklebreaker. Those weapons have a dura. Infinite combo does have not a dura.

Also: If your opponent does Retreating on SK or DMT, it causes even more hurt later.

Lastly, if anyone wants to try this in QM, I would suggest the following:

Majiya x1

Gargoyle x 4
Death Mage x 4
Shadow Knight x 4
Brutal Minotaur x 3
Fireball x 4
Lightning Strike x 4
tome x 4
Portal x 4
Shriek of Vengeance x 2
LLN x 2
Lamb x 2
nova x 1
DoU x 1

Play with it, then tuned it according to your preferences.

PS: Why so many "1" and "2"? well, if you like DoU and hate nova since Nova is killing your own allies, then - 1 nova, + 1 DoU. Vice versa, if you like the burn, remove the DoU, etc. The model is made so that you can play and see for yourself what's good and bad. 3 BMs, so that you can see for yourself how the Portalled BM is a nasty nasty pain-in-the-ass for your opponent; when you get more pro; drop to 2 BM. 2 Shrieks cos in QM, the opponents are not as tough as the WC finalist guys.  Blah, blah, you get the idea. Play and adjust the deck accordingly to your needs/ratings.


				1.2.2.2.2 Getting the best out of Portal (in a Majiya deck)

 

Let's start by introducing the card and explain what it does.

Card Name: Portal -> nothing to analyze here
Cost: (4) -> relative high card cost
Type: Mage Ability Support -> Cannot be destroyed by Stop Thief!
Details: Allies you summon for the next 3 turns can attack immediately (Haste)

Actually the text on the card is a bit misleading because Portal only stays on the board for the turn you played it and the next 2 turns (and not 3).

So you have for 3 turns the possibility to attack immediately with your allies if it doesn't get destroyed. Keeping that in mind you should see the following fact:

the more resources you have available and the more allies you have in your hand to use all the resources, the more use you can get out of every turn Portal stays on the board;
having allies with high attack value or high utility synergies very well with this card.

Using this facts Majiya becomes the best hero to use this card.  
Firstly she has access to the shadow allies that are created to have more damage than the human allies.
(nevertheless hasted human allies are also very strong, because they often have high utility -> see Lance)
Secondly Majiya's ability synergies more with Portal than Gravebone's ability, because that extra card you get really helps you to get to higher resources and so get more out of your Portal play.

___________________________________________________________________


So now we have the best hero for our Portal. Now let's find out the best use of Portal in game.
As I said earlier, the more allies you can haste through Portal in your 3 turns, the more you can get out of your card.
Keeping this in mind, playing Portal before you have at least 7 resources seems a bit wasted. Better even 8 resources. So you might ask yourself: "why this exact numbers?".
Hitting the magic number 7 with your resource count means you can play Portal and a useful (3) cost ally in the same turn, to not waste an entire turn of your Portal. In addition to that you can play a (5) fatty and another useful (3) ally the turn after. Same goes in the last turn of your Portal duration too.
If you play against a hero that can destroy the Portal (shadow or priest) it might be even better to wait until 8 resources to play the first Portal. Because then you can play your first Portal + (3) ally in the first turn, let him destroy your Portal and then play your second Portal + fatty in the next turn with 9 resources. If he is not able to destroy your first Portal you can play a fatty + two (3) allies then following it up with 2 fatties.

So you now could be thinking: "that looks amazingly strong, but it surely is hard to pull off and very theoretical!". Well honestly it is neither. Seeing this combo I explained, it's very hard to beat Majiya once she can pull it off successfully. This makes her one of the best high resource / late game heroes in the game.
And the shadow - mage card pool is exactly what she needs to get to this point, making it quite easy to pull this combo off nearly every game.
To see that, lets step back a bit. What do we need exactly? (obvious requirements -> hidden requirements)

High resource count -> board control + survive ability in the early game + card draw
decent amount of allies on your hand -> a lot of draw early- and midgame
A not hopeless board situation + decent amount of hit points -> early game board control

Seeing this should give you some hope, because the shadow mage card pool provides every single requirement.
With her burn spells + her ability Majiya naturally has good early game board control going first and second against most decks. The shadow early game allies also have good survive-abilities (Gargoyle, Brutalis, Bad Wolf) + a decent damage output.  
Combining the draw engines of mages (Tome of Knowledge) with her ability and the draw possibilities the shadow cards provide, we come to enough 1-sided draw to get to a high resource count in nearly every game. You also most likely get at least one, in most games even two, Portal on your hand, before you hit that point where you want to use them.

The last requirement is a bit more tricky. So surely you want to play your allies if you draw them and not want to keep back all your allies just to use them later with Portal. So bad news, you might think. Welcome in the double windmill.
But now the good news: as you might now, you need only 1 card to get out of this dilemma. The almighty Shadow Knight.
With him you can get back your allies you already played and lost in your early games. He has also a very high attack value and thus he has very high synergy with Portal by his own.

To sum this all up: the key cards divided in categories for the best use of Portal are:

Earlygame board control:

Fireball, Lightning Strike, decent amount of low cost allies (1) - (3)

Good draw:

Tome of Knowledge, Sacrificial Lamb or Bad Santa, Shadow Knight, Ley Line Nexus, (Belladonna)

Ally recycle:

Shadow Knight

High Damage allies:

Your favorite fatties, (5) cost allies
(I would not take Plasma Behemoth though, because you need the resources and cannot afford using his ability)

The card that makes everything possible:

Portal


An example for a Majiya deck I build with these rules:

Portal Majiya

1x Majiya
4x Gargoyle
4x Brutalis
4x Death Mage Thaddeus
4x Shadow Knight
3x Molten Destroyer
4x Fireball
4x Lightning Strike
3x Tome of Knowledge
4x Portal
2x Shriek of Vengeance
3x Sacrificial Lamb
2x Ley Line Nexus

So last but not least I want to talk about how you play in the several game stages.


Early game (0 resources - 7 resources):

Try to get and keep board control with burn, your ability and allies. Brutalis, Gargoyle and Death Mage Thaddeus are perfect allies to archive that. Bad Wolf and  Medusil also are very good. Use your burn spells together with the allies on your board to keep the side of your opponent clean.
If you can, drop a Tome on turn 4. Also don't be too reserved to use Sacrificial Lamb on your allies for more draw.
If you can, drop a fatty on turn 5. (don't drop Shadow Knight if you have no (3) ally at the top of your graveyard.)
Play as if you don't run Portal at all in a mid- late-game oriented deck, but try to keep 2 Portals in your hand if possible.
Aim to sac a card every turn. Sometimes its better to skip a sac but this is something you have to find out on your own.

Mid Game (7 resources - 10 Resource):

Use your Portal combo to either clean your opponent's board or to kill his hero.
Keep sacrificing cards.

Late game (10 resource +):

If you get to 10 resource and nobody won the game. you can step back a bit on sacrificing. Of course, higher resources are always good but you begin to run out of cards and so you may want to use all cards you draw.
Use Shadow Knight loop to have infinite access to fatties if he cannot deal with them.  (Shadow Knight loop also counters most mill decks).

 

Written by Painful_Smile
			1.2.2.3 Raphael Majere's Maj Deck: "Sacrificial Death Racer"
http://www.shadowera.com/showthread.php?12073-Test-Server-Pop-Tournament-Thursday-5-00-PM-%2817-00%29-GTM-0&p=164151&viewfull=1#post164151
Raphael Majere's Maj Deck: "Sacrificial Death Racer"

I am a consistency freak - which means I always aim for optimal card draw in all decks I make, essentially that meant Warriors in 1.25 onwards. Maj in 1.25 to 1.27. 

That also means I usually like 4 of everything - not 3. I use the either "2 or 4" rule.

Inspiration: YarikaSakin. Other people to thank: Wtzky and Kamman who taught me how to death race when I was in A1.

Allies: 

The Gang of 4: Brut, Garg, Bad Wulf, DMT.

The Burn: FB. LS, Nova

The Draw: Sac Lamb, Research

Tech: 3 LLN. (specficially for Spelleater bands)

Suprise, surprise: No oggy, No fatties.

Strategy: Play death race. 2 modes - Ally rush or pure draw/burn. 

For me, Maj is back as the deathracer - bye bye Elad. GB is ok, but I like Maj's board presence and card draw.

(Notes: GB is v good. Just not as death racer)

Sac Lamb is the key card: I think I won 2 games in tourney purely due to this card. All my opponents played very good decks. GB, Banebow, Zhanna. The only reason I won was due to me being able to death race faster than them, which meant my life was low as well. It does not matter: as long as at the end of game, I am the one with 1 more life than my opponent.

That put Sac lamb at a crucial spot. I can attack with Ally, do a sac lamb; draw 3 cards. and on the same turn, cast another ally out or do more burn. Combined with Maj ability, there is a lot of flexi-options for board control or DD burn to opponent. (late game Combo: attack hero with ally, sac lamb, Nova, board cleared, 3 cards drawn. 7 Resources needed. Next few turns: DD opponent to death)

I lost in finals for the same reason - lance was able to slow me down via Spelleater, Anklebreaker, and poison arrow. Lance took control of the pace of the game, instead of me taking the 'death-racer' lead.

Game 1 was close though. Ray top-decked just the right amt of dmg (Aldoned, Lanced-enhanced hasted Jasmine, 4 dmg) to finish me off. I would have won game 1 otherwise; but that does not matter cos I am likely to lose game 2 and 3 anyways.

