			1.3.1.1 Winning with Milkstalker - Complete Guild 
http://www.shadowera.com/showthread.php?17240-Winning-with-Milkstalker-Complete-Guild

Warning: If you are going to attempt to use this style of play, be prepared to be cursed at, yelled at, mocked, scorned, and hated by your opponent. Use at your own risk.

Perhaps the most hated deck in all of Shadow Era. Millstalker gets this notorious reputation because not only are the games "boring", they average about 30-45 minutes long. Some games can extended past 1 hour! Not exactly the "quick game" people are expecting during their 30 minute lunch break.

The reason people play this deck is because it is bloody effective at winning games. Played effectively, expect at least a 300+ rating with a 60%+ winning percentage in quick match. The majority of wins will come against Human deck because those heroes don't typically carry sufficient counters needed to defeat this deck. Many other wins will come from people quiting half way through the match due to frustration, boredom, or lack of time to complete.

Here are the core cards.

For milling:
Bazaaricon
Bad Santaicon

For defense:
What Big Teethicon
Evil Ascendent
Now Your Mine
Captured Preyicon
Crescendoicon

For stalling:
Shadow Fonticon
Rain Delayicon
Full Moonicon

For healing:
Lone Wolficon
Regenerate

Optional:
Shadow Knighticon
Speed Strike
Rabid Biteicon
Master Smithicon

The typical Millstalker deck will be composed of 46-52 cards. Don't be intimidated with this large deck size; you'll need everyone of them. This makes every sacrifice a crucial decision.

Bazaar: You want to play this card ASAP. If possible, play on turn 2. If your opponent is a human mage, hunter, or warrior, you can sack the remaining three. Those heroes can't destroy it. For all other heroes, try to save one in hand in case it becomes destroyed.

Bad Santa: Feel free to sack this card if a bazaar is out. Use it to find your critical Bazaar, Evil Ascendent, stalls.

WBT:

EA:

NYM:

CP:

Crescendo:


			1.3.1.2 Drakkon's Lazy Wolf & Hide n' Seek Stalker 
http://www.shadowera.com/showthread.php?8100-Drakkon-s-Lazy-Wolf-amp-Hide-n-Seek-Stalker

Welcome to my thread on "Lazy Wolf".


i. What is Lazy Wolf?
ii. Wulven Heroes
iii. Wulven Cards
iv. Shadow and Neutral Abilities
v. Drakkon's Lazy Wolf & Experimental Version


i. What is Lazy Wolf?


Lazy Wolf is a Wulven deck that focuses on using little to no allies to defeat your opponent. The two main sources of damage that this deck deals is from weapons and mill. Mill damage occurs when your opponent has no cards left in their deck. Each time they would draw they take 1 damage instead. This deck can be played with either hero. Both have their own advantages and disadvantages.



ii. Wulven Heroes


Lets take a look at the two current Wulven heroes you have to choose from.



Darkclaw is a pretty good hero for damage output. His ambush has some uses but is pretty lackluster right now. I'm guessing the usefulness of his ability will likely change in future sets.

Moonstalker is very good at preventing damage. His stall is unmatched and he is perfect for milling your opponent. His ability can only get stronger in time.



iii. Wulven Cards


In this section I'll be reviewing Wulven cards. Keep in mind, these are my opinions. No flaming if you don't agree.


This card is the main source of damage in the deck. Combined with Speed Strike this is some serious damage.
Run 4 copies of this card.

This card is the second piece of the puzzle. It allows you to stike twice per turn, and with Darkclaw's ability that's six damage. Combined with the ambush Darkclaw gives you can take down even some of the bigger threats without taking damage.
Run 3-4 copies of this card.

This is the bread and butter of the deck. It's what holds everything in place. You need this card to keep you alive while your opponents allies and weapons relentlessly attack you.
Run 3-4 copies of this card.

This card is one of the best ally removal abilities in the game. It has a very low cost and removes huge problem allies such as Infernal Gargoyal or Aldon the Braveicon.
Run 0-4 copies of this card.

This is, in my opinion, the best ally control ability in the game. It deals with EVERYTHING.
Run 4 copies of this card.

Now that Eladwin isn't 3/4 of every quick match this card isn't as necessary as it once was. Right now the current issue is allies. So why not run something that disposes of the ally rather than using a bandage?
Run 0-2 of this card.

The old MVP of the deck. It really has little to no use now because Darkclaw's ability doesn't have any form of inherent stall. So it's really just weird and out of place. It's kind of good against mages, but I really feel this card is just for Moonstalker right now.
Run 0-2 of this card.

Kind of a weird card. Personally, before the nerf I thought it was the best card in the game. Now, I've never even thought of using it. But it's actually kind of nice for using bigger allies to move smaller allies out of the way or putting some extra damage on a hero. I see other people using it. But I don't.
Run 0-2 of this card.


iii. Shadow and Neutral Abilities


This card is and will always be one of the key cards for people in Darkclaw. Currently, I'm playing 0 of this card. It's testing well, but at times I'm definitely missing this card. I'm thinking maybe a couple copies would be fine, but not 4. My reasoning is this.. Darkclaw has lost his inherent ability to defend himself, so this ability has basically lost half of the reason it was good. Darkclaw's damage output with this card is obviously high, but right now the decks biggest problem is survivability. So I've cut the Fonts for more control cards.
Run 4 of this card.

