	1.4 hunter

		1.4.1 Baduruu


			1.4.1.1 Morbius' killer Baduruu deck 2
Baduruu sure has come a long way, from being a weakest hero in the game when I published my first killer Baduruu deck, to being in the top half now and certainly the most utilized ranger. DP card pool has resolved most of his weaknesses and given him a lot of new options. Here is my best Baduruu deck so far, I hover around 290 rating with it.

Allies:
2x Infernal Gargoyle
2x Death Mage Thaddeus
2x Wendith Eagle-eye (attacks without retaliation and boosts bow damage up to 4)
1x Wolven Savage (saves you vs thieves)
1x Morbid Acolyte
2x Darkwood Wraith (saves you vs Elementalis and rushers)
1x Plasma Behemoth

Most of these allies are tough buggers who wont die from a single fireball. Remember that you draw 3 cards from using Sacrificial Lamb on any of them. 

Abilities:
2x Shriek of Vengeance
2x Poison Arrow
1x Acid Jet
1x Shadow Font
2x Ley Line Nexus
2x The Perfect Shot
1x Nocturnal Advantage
3x Sacrificial Lamb
1x Rapid Fire

Traps:
2x Enchanted Forest
3x Snare Trap
2x Rolling Boulders

Hero items:
2x Pride of the Mountain
3x Soul Seeker
4x Grundler's Double
1x Night Prowler

All together 44 cards with hero. You can cut or add some, based on the heroes you are facing the most. As it stands here, it is a very balanced deck with no huge weaknesses against any hero. Some match ups are very good for this deck, thieves being on top of the list, while you will generally fare worse against Darkclaw, Majiya and the warriors. Your biggest problem will be the lack of the reliable draw, so as usual with my ranger decks, you have several different draw mechanisms. Have fun owning!

		1.4.2
	1.5 warrior

		1.5.1 Amber 

			1.5.1.1 Amber - Reign of Champions
Introduction

So I decided to aim for top 100 in season 12 namely because it was a shorter season being only 28 days. I developed and used an Ambericon deck throughout most of the season. The deck served me well as it allowed me to be competitive with most match ups.

At the end of the season, my rating was 315 with win rate of 62%. My rating fluctuated between 320 to 330 throughout most the season. I purposely did not start playing with this deck until I hit a rating of 280 so as not to inflate my win percentage. I played a total of 253 games and 224 of them was with this deck. I finished with a rank of 77 with a score of 14,9540.

I named this deck "Ambericon - Reign of Champions" because a) the obvious play on the word "Rain" and b) I believe this deck has the best and most versatile allies out of all the human allies in the DP/COTC set - they are all champions in my book!

I thought it would be nice to share with you the deck itself, the rationale behind the build as well as some information on the different match ups I faced. So here it is! Enjoy! 


The Deck

~ Allies(17) ~
3x Champion of Irumicon
3x Jasmine Roseculticon
3x Aldon the Braveicon
3x Layarian Seductressicon
3x Armored Sandwormicon
2x Aeon Stormcallericon

~ Abilities(16) ~
4x Blood Frenzyicon
3x Bad Santaicon
3x Crippling Blowicon
3x Retreaticon!
2x Smashing Blowicon
1x Enrageicon

~ Items(6) ~
4x Jeweler's Dreamicon
2x Spectral Sabreicon

39 cards + hero


Build Raionale

Jeweler's Dreamicon & Blood Frenzyicon - this combination is what makes Amber the beast that she is today! With Blood Frenzy, you draw 2 cards per turn - this gives you card advantage. With Jeweller's Dream, you get 2 resources renewed - this helps you cast more cards which grants you tempo gain. With both card advantage and tempo gains, this then helps you regain or maintain board advantage. Sure you do lose 1 hit point per turn... but this is negligible early game. For more information on these concepts, check out "Converting one advantage to another" by Qazzaq
Champion of Irum: my ideal play is T3 Blood Frenzy so I need a T2 ally who will survive T3 solo often. Champion of Irum does this for me
Jasmine: I faced a lot of Moonstalkers and so i needed a way to deal with stealth. Jasmine helped me do this and she is a great T3 drop if I miss T3 Blood Frenzy
Aldon: he gives me the extra damage I need. His ability is amazing when you have multiple allies on board
Seductress: with Jeweler's Dream, I can comfortably match the amount of resources I have to my opponent. This often allows Seductess to trigger her ability and help me regain board control having lost it on T3 Blood Frenzy
Sandworm: I faced a lot of Ambers and Mages and so Sandworm worked well against both
Aeon: works so well against all heroes especially against Moonstalkericon as he could protect Jasmine from Now Your Mine
Bad Santa: if I do not have Blood Frenzy nor has my opponent played a card by T2, I will play Bad Santa on T2 to dig for a Blood Frenzy to play on T3. Bad Santa is also good for digging for certain cards needed urgently like an Enrage or a weapon
Crippling Blow & Retreat: both very useful on T2 going second and T4 with Jeweller's Dream. Crippling Blow is the better disable card generally so normally I will go 4/2 split. But since many Moonstalkers were stealthing Plasma Bohemoths and Tiger Wulfs ... I needed more retreats to counter this hence the 3/3 split
Smashing Blowicon: very useful against all classes T4 onwards except maybe Mages, hence only 2 included
Enrage: useful late game and against Mages
Spectral Sabre: such a versatile card! Use it to remove Blood Frenzy, Rapid Fireicon, Enrage and Speedstrikeicon... use it to free allies from disabling attachments... use it as a weapon!



The Match Ups

Eladwenicon
Record: 40 games played with a 60% win rate
Main deck(s) faced: a mixture of rush similar to Peithoson's Eladwen Red Deck Wins and control similar to Justicar's WC2013 Wildcard Qualifier Winning Eladwen Deck
Strategy: try to keep a weapon in hand and Sandworms on board as Eladwen struggles to deal with both these threats. Try to hang onto the Enrage or a Bad Santa to dig for the Enrage

Moonstalkericon
Record: 28 games played with a 54% win rate
Main deck(s) faced: allied based Moonstalker similar to Maskee's MS Dances with Tigers. There were a few Millstalkers similar to the one in Preybird's Moonstalker Breakdown
Strategy: obtain board control whilst countering Moonstalker's stealth ability on allies with Retreat, Crippling Blow, Seductress' summon ability and Jasmine's ability

Amber
Record: 28 games played with a 71% win rate
Main deck(s) faced: decks were similar to mine but more aggro with the use of Fleet Footed Messenger
Strategy: use Spectral Sabre to deny their Blood Frenzy draw and to use Smashing Blow to destroy their Jeweller's Dream.

Zhannaicon
Record: 21 games played with a 43% win rate
Main deck(s) faced: a mixture of Zhannaicon decks such as Klytz's popup winning Zhanna and SES Aphex's 55 deck Goddess Zhanna
Strategy: do not get behind in card advantage by a) getting rid of Zhanna's draw engines i.e. Wizent's staff and Elizabeth Winterborn b) not committing too many allies to the board so that the Tidal Waveicon does not trade well

Lanceicon
Record: 19 games played with 58% win rate
Main deck(s) faced: standard Lanceicon similar to the Lance in Preybird's Lance breakdown
Strategy: make good use of Retreat, Crippling Blow, Jasmine and Seductress to both keep board and counter Lance's hasted stealth allies. If you are about to lose board mid to late game, then consider rushing his health down instead of trying to regain board. Save Smashing Blow for Anklebreakericon if possible

Baduruuicon
Record: 18 games played with 67% win rate
Main deck(s) faced: semi resource denial decks similar to SES Night's 310 Baduruu
Strategy: both Blood Frenzy and Smashing Blow are crucial to this match up. Crippling Blow is useful for that one enemy ally that the Grundler's Double is relying on for draw. Sandworm is helpful for keeping board control and wearing down weapons.

Majiyaicon
Record: 14 games played with a 64% win rate
Main deck(s) faced: portal Majiyaicon similair to Raph's DP Portal Majiya
Strategy: try to have both a weapon in hand and Sandworm out. Make good use of Crippling Blow to halt any Shadow Knighticon loop. Try to hang onto the Enrage or a Bad Santa to dig for the Enrage

Zaladaricon
Record: 14 games played with a 64% win rate
Main deck(s) faced: Zaladaricon with Soul Reaper and Shadowvein similar to Yvan Antoine's Shadowveinicon Zaladar
Strategy: flood the board with allies with Sandworm being the most useful. Save Smashing Blow for Shadowvein. Try not use Enrage in case he steals it with Morphic Armoricon

Banebowicon
Record: 9 games played with a 89% win rate
Main deck(s) faced: standard Banebowicon similar to Index's Wrath of the Aggro Forest
Strategy: flood the board with allies and try to get Aeon to stick. Save Smashing Blow for bows and Wrath of the Foresticon.

Other Heroes
Results: 37 games played with a 65% win rate
Heroes faced: Serenaicon, Victoricon, Jericho, Borisicon, Ter Adunicon, Gravebone, Loganicon, Elementalisicon and Gwen



Concluding Remarks

I think it's important to note that this is not a tournament deck, it is a QM deck. In tournaments, your goal is win at every stage against all opponents - losses must be avoided if you are to progress. In quick match, your goal is to win consistently - losses are okay so as long as you make up for it with more wins.

Hence this deck doesn't have the odd Artful Squireicon for the odd Millstalker nor the odd Braxnorian Soilder for Lance. It simply concentrates on doing well against the Eladwen, allied Moonstalker and Amber; whilst still aiming to compete well with Zhanna, Lance, Baduruu, Majiya, Zaladar and Banebow.

Which leads me to reiterate how the allies in this deck are all champions! They are all so useful in many situations! 

I hope you enjoyed this! I'd be happy to answer any questions and receive any feedback.
