			1.6.1.5
		1.6.2 Jericho 

			1.6.2.1 2.0 Jericho "Black Sheep"
(a.k.a Advantage Me)

Hi all,

Ive been having a lot of fun and success with Jerichoicon lately, so I figured Id share my take on this underused and (really) underestimated hero:

Jericho

4 x Champion of Irum
4 x Jasmine Roseculticon
3 x Aldon the Braveicon
3 x Layarian Seductress
3 x Aeon Stormcallericon
3 x Elizabeth Winterborn

3 x Healing Touchicon
4 x Tidal Waveicon
4 x Focused Prayericon
3 x Retreaticon!
2 x Kings Prideicon

4 x Wizent's Stafficon

40 cards + hero

Optional:

+2 Ice Stormicon
-1 Healing Touch

Why Jericho?

This no doubt is your first question. At a glance theres nothing here to tie me specifically to Jericho, no attachments, no Lingering Essence, no trickiness. I chose Jericho at the time simply because of the meta, there were a lot of Ambers and Banebows around, and very little mage rush. Jericho was a good surprise package in a meta like this, as he can easily and reliably shut down Ambericon with little tempo loss to himself, and hes generally a tough prospect for Banebowicon provided he can keep Banes draw down. However Ive been genuinely surprised with his effectiveness against all heroes (gone 4-0 vs Portal Majiyaicon for example!)

Jerichos ability is also useful for freeing up your disabled and crippled allies, and just generally keeping them in the fight for longer than they have any right to be. When you factor in the negative effect part of his ability (which so many seem to forget), you realise Jericho is able to impact almost every hero in the game.

Draw

Lizzy is probably the next query you have, particularly as I dont have Zhannaicons heal to keep her undamaged. In my experience as long as you have other allies on the table, Lizzy is left alone as people go after the more immediate threats. This means that she will almost always equal or better Tainted Oracleicons draw, and heading into the late game with an Aeon shielding her she gives massive draw power. Coupled with Wizents (which Jericho can really exploit!) you can even outdraw warriors, which is a scary prospect in and of itself. In fact in one game with this I had decked myself while my opponent still had 20 cards left!

Quite simply this deck breeds draw and card advantage.

Tactics

Basically this deck plays like a more proactive Zhanna. You need early presence to soak up damage in preparation for your late game blitzing, and this is where Champ and Seductress really shine. In fact your early game control package is good enough to keep you in the fight in many cases and I have won games without using Tidal Wave at all. While Seductress seems counter intuitive given that Priests like high resources, she is worth her weight in gold in the early game, and in late game shes still a 4/5 with Kings Pride out which is nothing to be sniffed at. 

When it all comes down to it your goals are to control the board and more importantly to control the draw. When all goes to plan your opponent will have 1-2 cards in hand to your 6, and will be drawing 1 per turn to your 3. Thats when this deck steamrolls with ally after ally, and if Aeon dies with 3 in the deck youll have another ready. Healing Touch is a very important card against mages and Zaladaricon to give you enough breathing room to allow your superior late game to take off.

Conclusion

Thats my Jericho. Hes just like an old Volvo, solid and reliable with no fancy trimmings.

P.S: I was tempted to call the deck "Be Numb" 

P.P.S: If you're curious, I've been putting this deck through it's paces on ASF Preybird (bar that one match where I used Zal for old times sake).

