3. General 

	3.1 IRC 

		3.1.1 A Guide to getting onto IRC 
Hi all,

I'm pretty certain some of the newer members to the forum are a bit unfamiliar with IRC, so I thought I'd post this. It's a quick and dirty guide to get on IRC. It's not an in-depth listing of all the slash commands and tricks, but simply a way to get online so you can start playing those custom matches!

IRC is most easily used if you are on a computer, and GDC has created a couple of mirrors to the Shadow Era web interface with IRC built in a separate frame:

Live Server:
http://shadowera.gondorian.com/gamechat/

Test Server:
http://shadowera.gondorian.com/testchat/

To use IRC, all you have to do is specify a username. It can be anything you want it to be, but usually most players will use the same IRC name as their forum name (unless they're trying to go incognito ). You'll find most guild members will tend to place their guild's acronym in front of their IRC name. E.G. AA1-Seragyn, A1-Busti, TJ-Cwhit, ASF-Preybird.

Enter your chosen username, then fill in the Captcha keywords and click ok. On GDC's mirrors you'll be taken straight to the IRC Shadow Era room.

On the right hand side you can see a complete list of everyone online. Down the bottom is the message bar. Type what you want and it'll appear in the main window. This is the public space, and anyone can see what you type. If you want to send a message to someone in particular, you click on their name then select query from the sub-menu. A new chat tab will open up and anything you type will only go to that person. (Great for setting up tourney matches, or just catching up with a friend). To go back to public chat, you can click the Shadow Era tab up the top.

On mobile platforms, there are a couple of extra steps. Firstly you need to download an IRC client. I'm not familiar with all of them, but they should be quite similar. Download one and run it. I use AndChat for Android.

Chances are you'll need to put in a default username in all of these through their menu systems. As I'm not familiar with all of them, you'll need to follow their instructions. This username will be automatically applied every time you log in.

Shadow Era's room is part of the Freenode network, so make sure if you're given an option to choose your network, you use Freenode.

Anyway, once you're logged on, the biggest difference is that mobile IRC programs do not take you directly to Shadow Era's room, you need to tell it that's where you want to go. This is the command:

/j #Shadowera

the /j means join. (Pretty straightforward )

This will put you in the right chat room where you can set up games and chat to the other players.

Anyway, hope this helps to clear up any issues/misconceptions about IRC.

--------------------------------
I've written up a bunch of information about IRC for A1, this looks like a good thread to share it in. 

Getting on IRC
Via Webchat 

This is the simplest method to join the chat, and works in most browsers. Go to webchat.freenode.net and enter the following details (bits that look like {this} need you to fill in):
NickName: {your Forum Name}
Channels: #shadowera

Auth to Services: Check if you have registered your Nickname (see below.)

UserName: {your registered nickname}

Password: {your password}

Recaptcha: Do the silly captcha

Click connect, and after ~15 seconds you will be connected to the #shadowera chat channel.

Note: Gondorian has created framed pages that have the webchat and the game on the same page, which is great for when you are doing tournament matches. Try them out - Live Server - Test Server

Via an IRC client

There are a huge number of IRC clients available for every platform, if you want a more full featured chat, it's the way to go. Some clients recommended by A1 members are mIRC, AdiIRC, kvIRC, TurboIRC (for windows) and Colloquy for iOS and MAC.

Most IRC clients come preloaded with a list of servers to connect to, find and select freenode or enter irc.freenode.net in the server field. Enter your nickname and fill in any other required fields before connecting.

Once connected, type /join #shadowera to join the shadowera chat.

Registering your nickname
Registering your nickname brings a number of benefits. It allows you to reserve your name, and ensures that no one impersonates you. As well, once you are registered you can access additional channel commands. Bits that look like {THIS} need changing to suit you. Don't include the {} and it doesn't have to be caps.

1. Go in IRC. Get the nick you want using /nick {NICK}
2. In the status box, type /msg nickserv register {PASSWORD} {EMAIL}
3. Confirm your email address by following the instructions it contains.
4. When you log in, you will need to identify. If you have a section in your client to automatically perform commands on startup, put this there, otherwise, just type it in. /msg nickserv identify {PASSWORD}
5. Once done, if you want to prevent others using your nick use /msg nickserv set enforce on
This will change your nick after 30 seconds if you don't identify using the command in 4.
6. If someone (or you) tries to use your nick and fails to identify, it will lock it. use /msg nickserv release {NICK} {PASSWORD} to unlock it.
7. If at any time you forget a command. Use /msg nickserv help

You can also go further and use /msg nickserv help {COMMAND}
e.g. to remember how to use identify, type /msg nickserv help identify

FAQ's:

Q: I see people changing their nickname to let people know their status. How do I do that?
A: Type /nick {New Nickname}. It's good practice to register any nicknames that you commonly use with nickserv. To do so, make sure you have already identified with your main nickname. Change to your new nickname using /nick {NewNick} and then type /msg nickserv group.
Q: I have nickname protection on, but did not identify within 30 seconds of logging in. Now my name has been changed and I am unable to change it back. How do I fix this?
A: You need to release your nickname, change to it, and then identify properly. To do so, type /msg ChanServ release {Nickname} {pass} then /nick {Nickname} and then finally /msg nickserv identify {nickname} {password}
Q: I see some users have an @ sign. What does it mean and how do I get it?
A: The @ sign denotes an operator of the channel. They are able to control / moderate the channel. 
Q: Why is some text in different colours?
A: There are a few different reasons why there are different colours in chat. If someone types your name in chat, it will highlight the line in different colour, and depending on the client play a notification sound. You can 'emote' by typing /me <action> which will appear in a different colour for other users.

